,"stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Early diagnosis is common","Most patients are candidates for surgery","Obesity is a recognised risk factor","Steatorrhoea is an uncommon symptom","The disease has a good prognosis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPancreatic cancer has one of the poorest \u003Cstrong\u003Eprognoses\u003C/strong\u003E of all cancers, with a 5-year survival rate below 10%, making this cancer highly lethal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESmoking and \u003Cstrong\u003Eobesity\u003C/strong\u003E are both well-established risk factors. Obesity is now a recognised risk factor for a number of common cancers including oesophageal, breast, colorectal,  kidney, gallbladder, uterine, pancreatic and liver cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgery\u003C/strong\u003E is only possible in about 15-20% of cases as most patients present with advanced disease. \u003Cstrong\u003ESteatorrhoea\u003C/strong\u003E (fatty stools) is common due to blockage of pancreatic enzyme secretion. \u003Cstrong\u003EEarly diagnosis\u003C/strong\u003E is unfortunately rare as symptoms are often vague until advanced stages.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdditional features include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWeight loss\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAbdominal pain\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EJaundice if the tumour blocks the bile duct\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENew-onset diabetes in some cases\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pancreatic cancer has one of the highest mortality rates of all cancers","Steatorrhoea occurs in pancreatic cancer due to exocrine insufficiency","Most pancreatic cancers are diagnosed at an advanced stage when surgery is not possible"],"references":["Mizrahi JD, Surana R, Valle JW, Shroff RT. Pancreatic cancer. Lancet. 2020 Jun 27;395(10242):2008-2020. doi: 10.1016/S0140-6736(20)30974-0. PMID: 32593337.","Puckett Y, Garfield K. Pancreatic Cancer. [Updated 2024 Sep 10]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK518996/","Zhao Z, Liu W. Pancreatic Cancer: A Review of Risk Factors, Diagnosis, and Treatment. Technol Cancer Res Treat. 2020 Jan-Dec;19:1533033820962117. doi: 10.1177/1533033820962117. PMID: 33357065; PMCID: PMC7768873.","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50518"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15219"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50518","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50518"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-25T13:54:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-25T13:55:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7910"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65082"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+